Why isn't the Fed doing its job?
STANFORD – The nomination of new members of the US central bank, the Federal Reserve, gives people in America – and the US Congress – the opportunity to think about the most important central bank in the world and its future path.
The obvious, first question to ask is how it was possible for the Fed to如此 badly miss its most important mandate - ensuring price stability.
The fact that the Fed was completely surprised by the current inflation points to a fundamental failure.
Now, institutional self-examination is certainly appropriate.
Yet while monetary policy makes headlines, the Fed is now mainly significant as a financial regulator.
Another major question is therefore whether it will use its enormous power to advance climate or social policy.
The Fed could, for example, refuse to grant credit to companies in the fossil fuel sector, require banks to grant credit only to firms with certified net-zero emission plans, or direct credit allocation toward desired alternatives.
Moreover, she could decide to explicitly conduct her regulatory activities in the name of equality or ethnic justice by prescribing to banks where and to whom to grant credit, who to hire and who to fire, and so on.
Yet before we turn to the question of in which direction the Fed's regulation will or should move, it is first necessary to clarify the Fed's serious failure.
In 2008, the U.S. government made a fateful decision: while financial institutions could still largely obtain funds for risky investments by selling short-term, run-prone debt instruments, hordes of new regulatory agencies would henceforth assess the risk exposure of the institutions' assets.
The hope was that the regulatory agencies would no longer overlook large chunks of subprime mortgage-sized assets in the banks' balance sheets.
Yet in the following ten years of detailed regulation and regular scenario-based "stress tests," the Fed's regulatory army never once asked what would actually happen in the case of a pandemic.
When the pandemic actually occurred at the beginning of 2020, the Fed discarded its "never again" promises from 2008 and intervened on an even larger scale.
In March, the commercial banks proved unable to act as intermediaries in the market for plain vanilla U.S. government bonds.
Therefore, the Fed supported the market.
Critics had long pointed out the problems with the Fed's liquidity rules. The corrections on the markets would have been simple, but obvious reforms had been postponed.
Later, there was a run on money market funds.
The Fed once again rescued the money market funds.
Nothing is easier to fix than runs on the money market, but it never came to that.
Moreover, the Fed also financed the issuance of new municipal bonds and supported corporate bond prices by essentially offering a guarantee under the motto "Whatever it takes."
In 2008, the Fed and the U.S. Treasury had resisted the idea of raising the market price of all mortgages as part of the bailout package for the financial industry - the Troubled Assets Relief Program.
Yet in 2020, one had introduced an explicit floor for corporate bond prices, among other things, with the "Powell put."
The predictable response to this criticism will be: So what?
The lockdowns due to Covid-19 could have certainly triggered a financial crisis.
The flood of rescue measures has worked so well that our problem today is inflation.
We need not worry about systemic risks, because the Fed and the U.S. Treasury will simply put out every new fire with a new flood of money.
The problem lies, however, in the incentives these strategies have created.
Why go to the trouble of using reserves or balance sheet space to provide liquidity for purchases at falling prices or treating a "fire sale" as a "buying opportunity"?
The Fed will anyway outfly them all and collect the profits.
Why would companies still issue shares when they can simply take out a loan, knowing that the state supports the debt or helps the company out of trouble, as was the case with the airlines?
Why should investors hesitate when it comes to buying dubious securities, when their value is guaranteed in bad times by another "whatever-it-takes" promise from the Fed?
No wonder America is sinking into debt.
Everyone assumes that taxpayers will cover the losses in the next downturn.
Student loans, state pensions, and mortgages are piling up and waiting their turn to be rescued in Uncle Sam's bailout efforts.
But every new crisis requires even more extensive transfusions.
Bondholders will eventually refuse to put more money into bailouts and people will not enjoy having billions of newly printed money.
If the rescue packages expected by everyone do not materialize, we will wake up to a major fire — and the fire station will have been burned down.
In 2008, regulatory agencies and lawmakers at least still recognized the moral risk and were concerned that in good times investors would reap the gains while in bad times taxpayers would have to cover the losses.
In 2020, one indulged in complacency regarding the rescue operations.
Exactly the Fed, which in 2008 failed to foresee the risks of subprime mortgages just as it failed to anticipate the pandemic in 2020 and now wants to conduct stress tests with regard to "climate risks," will certainly also overlook the next war, the next pandemic, the next sovereign debt crisis, or another disruptive event.
The Fed regulators not even ask the question about the mentioned events.
And although jargon about "networking," "strategic interactions," "network effects," and "credit cycles" is produced, it has not been possible to define the "systemic" risk at all, aside from the fact that it has become a catch-all term that grants regulatory agencies sweeping power.
Regulatory agencies will never be able to foresee risks, accurately assess the assets of financial institutions, or ensure that enormous debts can always be repaid.
We must reverse the fundamental premise of a financial system in which the state always steps in to pay off mountains of debt in bad times. And we must do this before the fire department is put to the test.
Better regulation can bridge political divides.
The Left is right when it claims that the big banks are inefficient oligopolies that benefit most Americans little.
However, it is based on the wrong cause.
An immense effort to comply with regulations presents a major barrier to market entry.
The call for "more" regulation is senseless.
Regulatory provisions are either wise or foolish, effective or ineffective, full of undesirable consequences or well-conceived.
We need better regulation.
We need more capital, not thousands of pages of regulations.
Capital provides a buffer against all shocks and does not require regulatory authorities to have prophetic abilities.
The Fed has scandalously blocked companies in the Narrow Banking and payment services sector that could contribute to meeting the financial needs of many people in America.
Before it commits itself to saving the planet and making amends for injustices, the Fed should be held accountable for how poorly it fulfills its fundamental duty of protecting the financial system.
